post_text: Today, on #Juneteenth, we celebrate the history and stories of the Black community. The Pennsylvania Coalition of Public Charter Schools believes that a quality public education for all students, regardless of their zip code, is necessary to combat racism and inequality in our communities. Charter school leaders and their staff have dedicated themselves to improving the lives of Black children by providing them with an education that meets their unique needs. And, as educators we have a duty and responsibility to use education as the vehicle for continuous celebration of Black people to promote change. The reality of tomorrow cannot look like today, so we must seek to reimagine the learning environment to promote diversity and inclusion everyday. Read our full Juneteenth statement on our website --> http://pacharters.org/juneteenth-2020-reflecting-on-the-past-educating-students-for-a-better-tomorrow/

The following issuance timeline is also provided on the welcome page of the P-EBT Inquiry Form. SFAs may communicate this timeline to families as well.

P-EBT benefit issuance for current SNAP and TANF EBT cardholders will be complete by June 8, 2020, if their school-aged child was receiving free or reduced-price meals before May 20, 2020. Current SNAP and TANF EBT Cardholders can check their card balance by calling 1-888-328-7366 or using www.connectebt.com.

Free and reduced eligible school-aged students that are not SNAP/TANF or those receiving SNAP or TANF that became eligible for free or reduced-price meals after May 20, 2020, while P-EBT cards are being mailed and should be received by the end of June 2020.

post_text: Attention Parents/Guardians, due to low enrollment for the virtual summer boost program and parent feedback, we have decided to restructure the program so that we can offer extended learning opportunities to all students who would like to access them throughout the four week window. The program will now be asynchronous and activities will be posted through Summer BOOST Google classrooms. All K-8 students will have access to the new classroom codes, which will be posted in their current Google classrooms. Students will be able to earn BOOST points each week by completing the critical thinking challenges on the BOOST BINGO BOARD and will be eligible for gift card prizes through a weekly raffle! Please forward any questions you may have to Mrs. O'Brien. Thank you and stay safe.

shared_text:
Shooting For The Stars: Out of This World Connectivity

Grace3 Technologies LLC was live.
May 20 at 12:17 PM ¬∑

In collaboration with our partners, Dejero, an innovator in cloud-managed solutions that provide Emmy¬Æ award-winning video transport and Internet connectivity and NASA, Grace3 and Chariot Labs', a 21st-Century skills program for students lacking exposure to advanced STEM education are making it possible to access the live feed and stream the NASA SpaceX Demo-2 mission on May 27, 2020 beginning at 12PM on FBLive.

This historic launch led by NASA astronauts Robert Behnken and Douglas Hurley will be the first crewed launch from American soil in nearly a decade.

Not only that, but this will also be the first crewed launch that Elon Musk's aerospace venture SpaceX has ever performed, and the first time that humans have ever ridden on the Falcon 9 launch vehicle.

Don‚Äôt miss out on the opportunity to watch this historic event with your families, students, friends, and colleagues.

post_text:
The Executive Education Academy Charter School is pleased to announce that it has been awarded a $35,000 PAsmart Targeted grant from the Pennsylvania Department of Education. Funds will be used to provide professional training for teachers and to purchase technology and equipment in an effort to expand and enhance Computer Science and STEM education for our students.

In 2019, Executive Education Academy Charter School also received a Dollar General Youth Literacy grant for $3,000 and Lowe‚Äôs Toolbox for Education grant for $4,980. The Dollar General grant was used to purchase classroom guided reading collections to be used in small classroom settings in order to improve the literacy skills of our first graders. The Lowe‚Äôs Toolbox grant was used to purchase iPads for student use in our Career Awareness/Business Incubator Program.

Governor Wolf plans to announce additional Charter School Reform measures from Altoona School District tomorrow.
